Author: kreigdk
Content:
O Ocean Protocol facilita a troca de dados usando um protocolo descentralizado que combina NFTs de dados, datatokens e tecnologia Compute-to-Data (C2D). Os provedores de dados podem publicar seus serviços de dados como ERC721 Data NFTs e ERC20 datatokens, que permitem o controle de acesso descentralizado por meio de token-gating. Para acessar um conjunto de dados ou serviço de dados, é preciso ter os datatokens correspondentes. O consumo de serviços de dados envolve o gasto de datatokens.
O Compute-to-Data permite a compra e a venda de dados privados, preservando a privacidade. Ele permite que os cálculos sejam executados nos dados sem que eles saiam de suas instalações, garantindo que somente os resultados sejam visíveis para o consumidor.
O Ocean Market é um exemplo de um mercado de dados descentralizado em que compradores e vendedores podem trocar dados e algoritmos, com ferramentas para publicar e monetizar a propriedade intelectual usando a tecnologia blockchain.

Author: kreigdk
Content:
You can learn more here

https://oceanprotocol.com/learn/data-nfts-and-data-tokens
https://oceanprotocol.com/learn/compute-to-data

Author: semanticbeeng
Content:
Hello - my name is Nick Vintila, and am focused on building support for `machine learning engineering`, to bridge the gap from experimental analyses and data products,, between science and engineering. (as architect often need to puzzle together tech with duplicate functionality and conflicting designs)

In particular am working on a `feature registry` & `feature store` using `apache hudi`.
If you like any of the ideas here https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/HUDI/Hudi+for+Continuous+Deep+Analytics then would love to discuss.

Some topics that I am working from:
Hoping that these hash tags make it easier to find affinities and search.

`#DataGovernance` https://twitter.com/search?q=%23datagovernance%20(from%3Asemanticbeeng)&src=typed_query
`#MachineLearningEngineering`  https://twitter.com/search?q=%23MachineLearningEngineering%20(from%3Asemanticbeeng)
`#DataFabric` https://gist.github.com/SemanticBeeng/2edad7a5e2cd7cd6af5cde824b4e0da0
`#NonStationaryLearning`
  * https://twitter.com/search?q=%23Nonstationarylearning%20(from%3Asemanticbeeng)
  * https://twitter.com/search?q=%23ConceptDrift%20(from%3Asemanticbeeng)
  * https://twitter.com/search?q=%23covariateShift%20(from%3Asemanticbeeng)

Not a `blockchain` expert but am working on techniques to bridge between distributed application logic and `smart contract` functionality.

I studied `OceanProtocol` vision and high level design material quite a bit but not yet knowledgeable enough. If you think am missing some point please point me to material that I need to study.

Based on my understanding so far I do have some premises on how my work & focus relate to `OceanProtocol`. 
One of my first goals is to verify those premises with people here and their experiences.

Here's the first one https://twitter.com/semanticbeeng/status/1319889341074804736
> *"Data" needs to be a #dataGovernance "asset" before being a #blockchain "asset" because one cannot contract and trade in terms unless they are well specified.*

Author: semanticbeeng
semanticbeeng
Content: Also quite keen to learn about challenges in adoption and client / user requirements that may not fit with current design. What is the current process to digest these issues and potentially complement the current  functionality and design ?

Content:
Where is the latest discussion, work, etc on "compute to data" support, please? 
I am developing this multi-cloud, multi-tenant data mesh and there might be quite a bit of reuse possible.

Author: ryfleisch
Content: Hi! My name is Ryan. I’m a software engineer. I’m from michigan. In my day job, I work on SAP implementations for various large corporations and entities. For those unfamiliar - SAP is the application and database platform most Fortune 500 companies use to run their finance, procurement, manufacturing, order fulfillment processes of their business. I write code in SAP ABAP, but also node.js and other web app languages. SAP HANA is my passion!But more recently it’s also been blockchain. And Ocean genuinely stood out as something that could be immensely valuable for SAP implementations. I have some ideas to do some proof of concept work integrating Ocean protocol with SAP. But for now I just thought I’d say hi! 👋👋

Author: ssskylark
Content: Hi @ryfleisch great to have you on board! Ocean has some epic ecosystem projects happening right now. If you want to learn more about the details of Ocean, visit https://oceanacademy.io/. You can ask questions about the course in #🏛︱academy.

Author: robinlehmann
Content: An SAP integration would be really interesting. So much data resides in their databases that would be awesome to tap into. And as most of it is business critical, Ocean's technology to sell it without risking its leakage is incredible promising.

Author: ryfleisch
Content:
You’ve nailed it. The potential use cases are  as incredibly diverse as everything SAP gets used for. Most SAP systems today though are set deep behind corporate firewalls - and many go through double, triple, or quadruple spend  effort to get it into any kind of advanced data analysis. However - I think between the capabilities Ocean provides combined with some of the more cutting edge features of SAP HANA in particular (oData, standardized in-memory views, adoption of node.js and K8s for extension) make for some exciting possibilities. 

I’m going to walk through the ocean academy docs and in the meanwhile see if I can locate an appropriate SAP HANA sandbox for demo-ing how exchange data out of SAP into Ocean

Author: hebbianloop
Content: Hi, I just realized I never introduced myself! I'm Shady, a PhD in neuroscience and founder of Opscientia. My efforts have been dedicated to building a De-Sci (decentralized science) utilizing all of the benefits of web 3.0 to accelerate the pace of scientific innovation through peer-to-peer storage of massive datasets, confidential cloud computing, and sharing through data marketplaces. Our mission is to help transform the process of scientific discovery to include citizen scientists working together in parallel with traditional academia.

Author: mantisclone
Content:
I want to expand upon my initial introduction:

My name is David Hunt-Mateo and I'm a software engineer with 7 years of professional experience. For the last three years, I developed a cross-platform, on-device, noise-robust speech recognition library. Users liked it because it would work on whatever hardware they had, it never transmitted their audio to the cloud, and it would work in harsh environments like the middle of the ocean or a noise manufacturing floor. Unfortunately, I was laid off at the end of 2020. Soon after, I began reading about blockchain and was immediately enthralled by the benefits that decentralized Web 3 technologies could bring. I am currently participating in the KERNEL Block 2 fellowship program hosted by Gitcoin. 

I've spent 4 weeks researching to understand the Web 3 landscape and to determine exactly what use cases excited me most. I determined that I am most passionate about the user's right to privacy and data ownership, especially regarding AI and communication. Having developed a production AI system myself, I'm familiar with the massive amounts of data required as well as the difficulties small companies face when trying to acquire data. Furthermore, it's not hard to recognize the tactics that larger companies employ to extract data from their users. I think the Ocean Protocol could provide a solution to these problems, and furthermore, that it is poised for massive growth as the mainstream consciousness becomes aware of the abuse it's suffered at the hands of big tech. 

As such, the Ocean Protocol tops the list of projects I'd like to become involved with. My career has meandered through several industries and many layers of the technology stack. I consider myself a jack of many trades, adept at learning/applying new technologies, and a skilled communicator. My specialties in the past have been cross-platform development, desktop and native Android apps, and embedded software.

Author: ssskylark
Content:
What sets Ocean apart is, simply allows data sales without losing control over the IP on the data - this is especially useful for machine learning/AI tasks. The algorithms can train a model on data without the data leaving the owners premesis. This enables data usage that was not possible before e.g. for medical data.

Additionally it also enables the creation of datatokens and liquidity pools for datasets which allow for price discovery, curation and reputation of datasets. High quality datasets will have different setups of their datatokens than unsuccessful ones.

Content: Hello Everyone! Thanks @Sheridan | Ocean Protocol for giving me an intro. My name is Mats Brodén based in Stockholm, Sweden. I'm the curator for a multi-stakeholder ecosystem called Sense Nation. We are exploring the interface between nanotech and DLT together with onboarded companies that drive demand. We want to reach out to the Ocean community in order to expand our imagination capacity when it comes to DLT and Nanotech. In a way we blur the line between the physical and the digital. We are building or rather measuring out a hidden asset layers in matter. Looking forward to connect to you. I'm happy to give you an intro on what we are doing. All the best mats@embeddednano.com

Author: robinlehmann
Content:
Wow, sounds highly interesting!
I kind of lost touch with recent development in Nanotech. Would love to know more how this will look like.

Are these projects like nanobots getting paid to repair my body? Or more in industrial production?
Awesome to have you in the community!

Author: matsbrodennordicpowerhouse
Content: Hi Robin, thanks for your questions. Well we will focus on nano sensors that "dig" up unique data. It is kind of dynamic identities that will make it possible, via AI, to ask material systems like machines and organisms how they are doing. An ontology of a thing.  Initially we will focus on machines and predictive maintenance. It will be possible to do what you ask but as a first step it will as feedback loop. I'm curios to ask you how we can develop this into something that can address for instance the oracle problem. Feed smart contract with data.

Author: robinlehmann
Content:
Wow, that sounds interesting.
I am working as AI program manager at Rolls-Royce Power Systems where I am also concerning myself with predictive maintenance for production machines, engines etc.
Additionally I did my master and bachelor thesis years ago on the same topic.

Fascinating field. If you want to discuss this in a call and how this could work with Ocean Protocol I would be glad to do that.

Author: matsbrodennordicpowerhouse
Content: Sounds excellent. You are a precursor when it comes to digital twins. We are exploring one sensor at the moment that might be relevant for you. Yes, let's set up a call.

Author: stippes
Content:
Hey guys!
Looking forward to learn more about the Ocean Protocol.
I am working for a research institute in the Netherlands and we are looking at the blockchain to save our participant data in an open and transparent manner (although it is a pretty early stage pilot project)
Do you know whom I could talk to that is familiar with the use of psychometric data on the blockchain? 
Or any pointers towards good learning material are also welcome.

Author: robinlehmann
Content:
You should try https://OceanAcademy.io - this gives a good introduction to Ocean Protocol.
In Ocean Protocol the data is not stored on the blockchain but the governance is organised via the blockchain. So the data resides on premise and the access to the data by algorithms is organised via compute-to-data. This means that the data is not going to leave the data storage and that the data owner (you) can allow algorithms to access the data or not.

Author: youaintmyfry
Content: What does this platform do in a nutshell? And how is it a necessity? And does it have the potential to be globally used?

Author: robinlehmann
Content:
Allow the sharing/selling of data without allowing it to be copied.
This is a necessity to open up the data silos of data that either cannot or does not have to be moved either due to size or privacy concerns.
There are several projects building on top of it to use it for global software but the marketplace itself is also globally available.

Author: youaintmyfry

There is the OceanDAO which funds projects building on top of it month by month - check it out here: https://oceanprotocol.com/dao
Right now the 8th round is ongoing.

Author: Miriam RAZ#9864
Content:
Hi Ocean DAO Community! My team and I at RAZ Finance appreciate your support and the grant we received during Round 8. A new, more conscious, generation of investors and stakeholders expects meaningful progress towards the Sustainable Development Goals alongside positive impact and ESG outcome realization. 

By 2025, 1/3 of global assets under management, representing 53 trillion dollars, will be classified as “Sustainable” and  “Environment, Social and Governance” investments.

Although regulations are emerging that mandate disclosures, self-reported data just isn’t enough anymore.

It’s time to raise the bar. 

Our team is driven by a strong commitment to making it possible for talented founders to realize their potential through tangible, verified, technology-driven data. 

Through an equitable investment lens catalyzed by blockchain technology, RAZ will open doors for funding to be channeled towards world-changing social and environmental innovation

Author: rikrapmund
Content:
Hi everyone! My name is Rik Rapmund, supporter of Ocean since the ICO and founder of WorkPi: an HR Tech startup that predicts the required skills for rapidly evolving jobs in organisations to reduce skill gaps and eliminate mismatches. Besides WorkPi we are also building Work X: a decentralized platform economy for work where service providers and customers can work together without intermediaries. 

Because we believe that the personal data of our users should be owned and controlled by themselves, we are working together with the European Commission on a Self-Sovereign Identity solution (SSI). Users will be able to connect their career related data such as assessments, diplomas, certificates or references to their digital passport/identity. This is also where Ocean comes along. It's a great thing to give data back to the people, but is also comes with a challenge: how do we learn from it when the data is scattered around the world? The technology of Ocean is very promising to solve this problem. To this end we introduce *Compute-to-SSI*. Learn more about our proposal here: https://port.oceanprotocol.com/t/workpi-oceandao-round-9/862

We're very interested to get to know the community and hear your feedback! 

Cheers! 

Rik

Author: savvak
Content: Hi, I am a IP/crypto/biotech lawyer, patent attorney and founder of the DeSci project https://crowdfundedcures.org which is partnered with and advises DeSci projects VitaDAO.com and Molecule.to. Our mission is to use pay-for-success (PFS) smart contracts and IP-NFTs to solve a trillion dollar market failure due to misaligned incentives under patent system and bring an open source business model to biopharma by incentivising the repurposing of generic/off-patent drugs for 1/100th of the cost of patented drugs. I presented at DeSci day in ETHAmsterdam (https://youtu.be/40UeWLDutYo) and we are currently working with Longevity Prize (https://twitter.com/longevityprize) to raise $1m in payer funds for an IP-NFT x PFS pilot to support a Phase 2 clinical trial by Dr Brad Stanfield to use off-patent rapamycin + exercise to improve healthy longevity in the elderly - see attached diagram. We think Ocean Protocol would be a key partner to help scale the generic drug repurposing PFS x IP-NFT model.

Author: filippo305
Content:
Hello, I am new to this forum so I hope you'll forgive the 'shotgun' and long post until we find a more precise channel and thread:
1. We are looking for technical/strategic support to explore adoption/implementation/grant-application of Ocean Protocol (or similar DAO) for our startup (developing the world's first personal safety barometer - just launched our Reg CF campaign):  https://wefunder.com/safe-esteem
2. We believe our business and mission represent the quintessential application of the DAO Economy and Compute-to-Data Architecture: We are creating (and have a patent for) a universal personal life risk scoring system (accidents, crime, health). Think of it as the FICO score of life risks - but owned by each individual (instead of credit rating firms) who can participate in the larger market/economy of brokers, insurers et al, while preserving privacy and allowing increasingly sophisticated risk (and safety) models. 
3. I just used an adapted version of the Ocean Compute-to-Data Architecture graph for remarks at the United Nations Climate and SDG Synergies Conference https://www.un.org/en/climate-sdgs-conference-2022/page/side-events (with very clear attribution) to highlight the opportunities of a DAO/NFT approach to risk data (I hope the Ocean folks won't be upset - it was a last opportunity - happy to coordinate on the next event.
Thank you - I'll take any suggestions/recommendations on how to best leverage this forum to achieve the above.

Content:
**Hey frens, I’m Chris!** I’m a 24yo full-stack dev living in Boston, USA. I was a data & automation architect at Celsius (pre-bankruptcy), built SheetLink (Sheet.Link), and I'm now a full-time builder/dog-dad alongside my amazing wife & co-founder.

**We're building Fide** (Fide.id). Fide empowers cross-chain discovery and investigation. We help teams find and evaluate investment/partnership/growth opportunities based on their reputation, relationships and digital activity.

**I could help** any builders with a use case in alignment with our mission of enabling informed decisions in the web3 space. Our web-app, API, and data enrichment solutions are intentionally flexible to deliver data where & when it's needed most.

Author: .humility.
Content: I currently spend my time being a DAO Practitioner. Being a DAO Practitioner simply means healing communities, such as DAOs, by being a voice of reason and respect to as many people as possible. My passion is to treat people with love and respect, regardless of if they hate me or not. This is because it isn't about me, and I am passionate about selflessness.

Author: .humility.
Content: My Idea is to evolve common human perception by culminating viewpoints with a median of understanding. By looking at 2 different viewpoints, for example, and bringing the opposing viewpoints together, we can find new ways to look at ideas, therefore finding new ideas to begin with. I believe that because web3 gives more value to individuals and information, something I would like to call "valueless information" will exist. This will allow more people to understand that knowledge alone can be useful for social interaction, and therefore strengthen communities. By being a DAO practitioner, this is what I am here for. To make knowledge as open-source as possible, and grant higher quality lives to every living human in a structured society.

Author: vintro1873
Content:
hey everyone 👋  i'm vintro -- a data scientist with a background in applied NLP + web3 analytics and professional experience in web3 + higher education. i'm currently building prototypes for an AI tutor with some partners from the education space 👀 . i've long been a fan of ocean for creating economic systems around data tasks. currently, i'm exploring how i can use ocean to reward humans in the loop for labeling desired outcomes and training a reward model. giving folks an "equity" stake in the model they help train is much more ethical than one-time ~~exploitation~~ payment for their human services.

if anyone has more detailed resources to share, i'd be grateful for anything. and if AI tutoring sounds like an interesting problem to you, let's chat about it!! i've been deep down the web3 rabbithole for the past ~2 years so i'm getting back up to speed with the recent advances in transformer-based models. i'd love to meet anyone who wants to jam on ideas around how this ml pipeline could work. thanks ✌️

Content: Hello @vintro  Good to have you here! Amazing background and idea. Please check this channel for co-op #✨︱find-a-team-old . Good luck!

Author: idiom_bytes
Content:
Vintro, you should check out our data challenges, specifically the predict-eth challenge. You might be able to contribute something to it.

With regards to labeling and human-in-the-loop, it might be interesting to see how DataUnion structured their operational model.

Basically, users are rewarded for both sharing data, in addition to labeling it.

And as you pointed out, are rewarded as part of a union, owning shares of that DAO, rather than receiving a flat fee and being done.

Welcome to the Discord!

Author: idiom_bytes
Content:
Awesome project JP, love the fitness/exercise space and hopefully you find a fit here.

There are many ways to leverage Ocean to enhance your business model and there might be different points to start from.

Author: .anatix
Content:
Hi everyone, I am a developer and consultant and came across OCEAN protocol since I am looking for some BC tech for a customer that is producing huge amount of data and is looking into publishing them / selling them for certain use cases. I read the white paper and watched some videos but I fail to understand two things:

- if data is "hidden" behind a certain URL, how exactly is a "client" reading the data without getting aware of this URL? Or is he getting the URL? If so what hinders him to re-visit this URL at any time in the future? Will the URL stay hidden for ever? If so:  who is accessing the URL on behalf of the client?

- if I (as a "client") have bought a data token, what hinders the publisher to take down his data? This would make my bought data token worthless. Do clients simply have to trust that publishers do not take down assets? 

Would be great if you could provide some reference for clarification.

Content:
Dear Ocean Protocol,
I hope this message finds you well. I am reaching out to you today( Ocean Protocol team) to discuss the benefits of joining the Joystream YPP program and bringing your content from YouTube to our platform.
By joining the YPP program, you will receive free marketing and extra awareness from the Joystream community. This will require only a few clicks from your side and will be absolutely free. Additionally, you will have the opportunity to backup your YouTube content on a web3 media platform, ensuring that your content is secure and accessible to a wider audience.
As a YPP member, you will also receive free JOY tokens for sign-up, as well as access to NFTs on Joystream that can help to engage your community. Furthermore, Gleev allows only crypto-related content, which means that you will have a better audience quality and more targeted exposure.
By joining in the early stages, you will receive high-level support from the Joystream DAO, including promotion of your channels on Twitter, Discord, and within the platform itself. We are committed to helping our YPP members succeed and will provide incentives and other benefits to ensure your success.
I believe that your project would be a great fit for the Joystream platform, and I would be happy to answer any questions you may have about the YPP program or our platform in general. Thank you for your time, and I look forward to hearing from you soon.
Best regards,
Genius

Content:
Hello.  My name is soulman, an experienced individual with a deep passion for fostering meaningful connections and driving engagement, I am committed to creating a dynamic and vibrant online community.

Key Highlights:
1. Community Moderation: I will maintain a respectful and inclusive environment by monitoring discussions, addressing concerns, and encouraging positive interactions among members.

2. Twitter Promotion: Through strategic content creation and consistent engagement, I will increase the project Twitter presence, attracting new followers and building excitement around the project.

3. Chatter Engagement: Been a team of 10-20 people. Who will be chatting daily in the project Telegram or Discord community group about the project and also serves as investors of the project too as well.

4. Social Media Management: With a strong understanding of various platforms, I will curate and schedule content that resonates with the project audience, sparking conversations and fostering a sense of belonging.

5. Ambassadorship: I will embody the values of the project, both online and offline, by attending events, collaborating with partners, and promoting the project mission.

Together, we can amplify the project voice, elevate its visibility, and cultivate an engaged and enthusiastic following. Thanks for taking the time to read, Regardless of whether or not we work together, I'm a fan of you and your work.

I look forward to the opportunity to contribute to the growth and success of the project.

Content: Hi, yes I am evaluating several AI Projects, I want to build a Plattform where you can select LLMs and compare it to each other. A use case is for example, a user creates a workspace and want to write a book with the support of a LLM lets say gpt 4, so he starts to explain  whats about and then he starts to mark the most suitable answer and save the outcome in his workspace.  The problem with common LLMs is that the context get lost if your token size is limited. therefore the system should keep the context intactand if the user asks lets say in chapter 22 about Kreig, the system should get the context and based on that the user can continue his progress...This is only a use case, but you can rely this pattern in different scenarios, for example code snippets from LLMs ai prompts to an entire project

Author: kreigdk
Content:
Hey!  We're glad to see you here in the Ocean Protocol community😎🌊

To start learning about Ocean Protocol and its role in creating a decentralized data marketplace, you can follow these steps:

Understand Ocean Protocol's Mission and Core Technologies: Ocean Protocol aims to level the playing field for AI and data by enabling the monetization of AI models and data while preserving privacy. Its core technologies include Data NFTs & datatokens for token-gated access control and Compute-to-Data for buying and selling private data while preserving privacy.

Explore What You Can Do with Ocean: Depending on your interest or expertise, you can engage with Ocean Protocol in various capacities such as a builder, data scientist, or OCEAN holder. Each role offers different opportunities, from building token-gated AI dApps and APIs to earning rewards through data farming.

Join the Ocean Protocol Community: Becoming an Ocean ambassador is a great way to get involved. You can join Ocean Protocol's Discord server, participate in discussions, and apply to become an ambassador through the #treasure-hunter channel on Discord.

Learn Through Doing: Consider participating in data challenges hosted by Ocean Protocol to apply your skills in real-world problems and earn prizes.

Dive Deeper into Documentation: Visit the Developers and Data Scientists pages on Ocean Protocol's website for step-by-step instructions, APIs, libraries, and other tools to build dApps or integrate with the Ocean ecosystem.

Stay Informed: Keep up with the latest updates and resources by following Ocean Protocol's official channels and participating in community events.

https://oceanprotocol.com/

https://market.oceanprotocol.com/

Author: kreigdk
Content:
And if you want you can try Data Farming

Data Farming https://df.oceandao.org/  is Ocean's incentive program that rewards OCEAN to participants who lock OCEAN into veOCEAN, curate data, or make predictions. It aims to drive data consume volume (DCV) and is similar to DeFi liquidity mining but tailored for DCV.

Content: @OceanGPT what are the ocean protocol fees?

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: Hello Mihai! The Ocean Protocol has various fees for creating a sustainability loop. For swaps involving approved base tokens like OCEAN and H2O, the Ocean Community swap fee is 0.1%. For swaps involving other base tokens, the Ocean Community swap fee is 0.2%. The Ocean Community order fee is 0.03 DT per order operation. Provider fees are paid to the individual or organization running their Provider instance when the user orders an asset. These fees can be set to an absolute amount, not as a percentage. Let me know if you have any other questions!

Author: swish24_08
Content: can you tell me about the provider fee?

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: Of course, Mihai! Provider fees are paid to the individual or organization running their Provider instance when the user orders an asset. These fees can be set to an absolute amount, not as a percentage. The provider can also specify which token the fees must be paid in - they don't have to be the same token used in the consuming market. Provider fees can also be used to charge for computing resources. Based on the compute resources needed to run an algorithm in the Compute-to-Data environment, a consumer can choose the amount to pay according to their needs. Let me know if you have any other questions!

Author: bogdanoceanprotocol
Content: @OceanGPT what is the role of Provider in ocean protocol stack

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: The Provider is a component of the Ocean Protocol's ecosystem that facilitates data consumption, starts compute jobs, encrypts DDOs, and decrypts DDOs. It also validates if the user can access a particular data asset or service. The Provider fees are paid to the individual or organization running their Provider instance when the user orders an asset. These fees can be set to an absolute amount, not as a percentage, and can be used to charge for computing resources. The Provider can also specify which token the fees must be paid in - they don't have to be the same token used in the consuming market. These fees incentivize individuals and organizations to run their Provider instances and charge consumers according to resource usage.

Hello! The possible states of a dataset inside Ocean Protocol are:

1. **Unpublished**: A dataset that has not been published on the Ocean Protocol network.
2. **Published**: A dataset that has been published on the Ocean Protocol network but is not yet available for consumption.
3. **Consumable**: A dataset that has been published on the Ocean Protocol network and is available for consumption.
4. **Consumed**: A dataset that has been consumed by a user on the Ocean Protocol network.

Author: sheridan_oceanprotocol
Content: @OceanGPT Can your explain the difference between datatokens and dataNFTs as well as provide details as to what they are used for and why.

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
Sure, I'd be happy to explain the difference between datatokens and data NFTs in Ocean Protocol.

Data NFTs are non-fungible tokens that represent a unique piece of data, such as a dataset or a data service. Each data NFT is unique and can be owned by a single entity at a time. Data NFTs can be traded on data marketplaces, allowing data providers to monetize their data assets.

Datatokens, on the other hand, are ERC20 tokens that represent a fractional ownership of a data NFT. They allow for the creation of a market for data, where data providers can sell fractional ownership of their data assets to multiple buyers. Datatokens can be traded on decentralized exchanges and used in DeFi applications.

In summary, data NFTs represent unique pieces of data, while datatokens represent fractional ownership of those data NFTs. Together, they enable the creation of data markets and the monetization of data assets.

Author: swish24_08
Content: @OceanGPT how can i create a fixed rate exchange in ocean.py?

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
To create a fixed rate exchange in ocean.py, you can use the `create_fixed_rate_exchange` function from the `ocean.py` library. Here's an example code snippet:

```python
from ocean_lib.config import Config
from ocean_lib.ocean import util
from ocean_lib.ocean.util import from_base_18
from ocean_lib.web3_internal.wallet import Wallet
from ocean_lib.models.data_token import DataToken
from ocean_lib.models.fixed_rate_exchange import FixedRateExchange

# Set up configuration and wallet
config = Config('config.ini')
wallet = Wallet(config.parity_address, config.parity_password)

# Set up data token and exchange parameters
dt = DataToken(config, config.metadata_store_url, wallet)
dt_name = 'My Data Token'
dt_symbol = 'MDT'
dt_total_supply = 1000
exchange_rate = from_base_18(1)  # 1 OCEAN = 1 MDT

# Create data token and mint initial supply
dt.create(dt_name, dt_symbol, dt_total_supply, from_wallet=wallet)
dt.mint(wallet.address, dt_total_supply)

# Create fixed rate exchange
exchange = FixedRateExchange.create(
    config,
    wallet,
    dt,
    exchange_rate,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply,
    dt_total_supply
)

# Print exchange information
print(f"Exchange ID: {exchange.exchange_id}")
print(f"Exchange contract address: {exchange.contract_address}")
```

This code creates a new data token, mints some initial supply, and then creates a new fixed rate exchange for that token with a 1:1 exchange rate with OCEAN. You can adjust the exchange rate and other parameters as needed for your use case.

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
To create a dispenser in Ocean.js, you can use the `createDispenser` function from the `ocean.js` library. Here's an example code snippet:

```javascript
const ocean = await Ocean.getInstance({
  web3Provider: 'http://localhost:8545',
  nodeUri: 'http://localhost:8545',
  aquariusUri: 'http://localhost:5000',
  brizoUri: 'http://localhost:8030',
  brizoAddress: '0x00bd138abd70e2f00903268f3db08f2d25677c9e',
  secretStoreUri: 'http://localhost:12001',
  verbose: true
})

const dispenser = await ocean.dispenser.createDispenser({
  amount: '100',
  tokenAddress: '0x1234567890123456789012345678901234567890',
  from: '0x1234567890123456789012345678901234567890',
  to: '0x0987654321098765432109876543210987654321',
  interval: 86400, // 1 day
  startTime: Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000),
  endTime: Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000) + 86400 * 30 // 30 days
})

console.log(`Dispenser created with ID: ${dispenser.id}`)
```

This code creates a new dispenser that will distribute 100 tokens over a period of 30 days, starting from the current time. You can adjust the amount, token address, recipient address, interval, start time, and end time as needed for your use case.

Content: @OceanGPT how can i set allowed publishers on an algorithm?

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
To set allowed publishers on an algorithm in Ocean Protocol, you can use the `ALLOWED_PUBLISHERS` metadata field when publishing the algorithm. This field restricts metadata caching to publishers in a specified list of publisher addresses.

Here's an example code snippet using `ocean.py`:

```python
from ocean_lib.config import Config
from ocean_lib.ocean import util
from ocean_lib.web3_internal.wallet import Wallet
from ocean_lib.models.algorithm import AlgorithmMetadata

# Set up configuration and wallet
config = Config('config.ini')
wallet = Wallet(config.parity_address, config.parity_password)

# Set up algorithm metadata and allowed publishers list
metadata = AlgorithmMetadata(
    {
        "base": {
            "name": "My Algorithm",
            "description": "A sample algorithm",
            "author": "John Doe",
            "license": "MIT"
        },
        "custom": {
            "parameters": {
                "param1": "value1",
                "param2": "value2"
            }
        }
    }
)
allowed_publishers = ['0x1234567890123456789012345678901234567890', '0x0987654321098765432109876543210987654321']

# Set the allowed publishers field in the metadata
metadata.set_allowed_publishers(allowed_publishers)

# Publish the algorithm
algo_ddo = ocean.assets.create(metadata, wallet)
```

In this example, we create an `AlgorithmMetadata` object with some basic metadata and a custom parameters field. We then set the `allowed_publishers` field using the `set_allowed_publishers` method on the metadata object, passing in a list of publisher addresses. Finally, we publish the algorithm using the `create` method on the `ocean.assets` object, passing in the metadata and wallet.

```javascript
const computeJob = await ocean.compute.startComputeJob(
  computeJobId,
  algorithmDid,
  algorithmMeta,
  inputFiles,
  outputFiles,
  providerUri,
  providerAddress,
  consumerAddress,
  consumerToken,
  consumerWallet
)
```

In this example, we use the `startComputeJob` function to start a compute job. We pass in the compute job ID, algorithm DID, algorithm metadata, input files, output files, provider URI, provider address, consumer address, consumer token, and consumer wallet. The function returns a promise that resolves to the compute job object.

Content: @OceanGPT How exactly does Ocean protocol token-gating work?

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: In Ocean Protocol, token-gating refers to the process of requiring a certain amount of tokens to access or use a particular data asset. This is done through the use of datatokens, which are ERC20 tokens that represent a specific data asset. The owner of the data asset can set a certain amount of datatokens as the access fee for the asset, and users must hold that amount of tokens in their wallet in order to access the data. This creates a market for the data asset, as users must purchase the necessary tokens in order to access the data. Token-gating can also be used to incentivize data providers to share their data, as they can set a higher access fee for their more valuable data assets.

Author: christian_casazza
Content: @OceanGPT Explain in detail what information is held in a data NFT and what information is held in a datatoken

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
A data NFT (ERC721) represents a unique data asset and contains metadata such as the asset's name, description, and creator. It also includes a reference to the asset's DID (Decentralized Identifier) and DDO (Decentralized Data Object) which contain additional information about the asset such as its location and access control policies.

On the other hand, a datatoken (ERC20) is used to access data services and represents a certain amount of access to a specific data asset. It contains information such as the amount of access it provides and the address of the data provider.

During the purchase flow, Aquarius is used to store and retrieve metadata about the data asset, while Provider is used to manage access control and provide access to the data asset. Datatokens are used to transfer access to the data asset from the buyer to the data provider.

Aquarius stores metadata off-chain and can be run locally or remotely. Running Aquarius locally allows for more control over the metadata and faster access to it, while pointing to a remote instance allows for easier maintenance and scalability.

The advantage of running Aquarius yourself instead of using the REST API is that you have more control over the metadata and can customize it to your specific needs. It also allows for faster access to the metadata and reduces reliance on external services.

It is possible to utilize Ocean Protocol without using Aquarius, but it would require manually managing metadata and access control policies, which can be time-consuming and error-prone. Aquarius provides a convenient and standardized way to manage metadata and access control for data assets.

This means that the access control information for an asset on Aquarius is encrypted and can only be accessed by the Provider who holds the private key for that specific instance of Aquarius.

It is responsible for accessing and providing data assets, performing checks on chain for buyer permissions and payments, encrypting the URL and metadata during publish, decrypting the URL when the dataset is downloaded or a compute job is started, providing access to data assets by streaming data, and providing compute services. Provider is typically run by the Data Provider. To run your own provider, you can clone the repo and understand the config parameters, envvars vs files, and learn about off-chain services such as Ocean Provider for data services and Aquarius metadata store.

Author: christian_casazza
Content: @OceanGPT Walk me through the steps of running my own provider

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
Sure, here are the steps to run your own provider:

1. Clone the provider repository:
```bash
git clone git@github.com:oceanprotocol/provider.git
cd provider/
```

2. Initialize the off-chain services (Aquarius and Provider) by cloning the Barge repository and running it:
```bash
git clone https://github.com/oceanprotocol/barge.git
cd barge/
./start_ocean.sh --with-provider2 --no-dashboard
```

3. Set up the environment variables in your `.env` file:
```
FLASK_APP=ocean_provider/run.py
PROVIDER_ADDRESS=your ethereum address goes here
PROVIDER_PRIVATE_KEY= the private key or string containing a dict of chain_id to private key pairs
PROVIDER_FEE_TOKEN = the address of ERC20 token used to get fees, or string containing a dict of chain_id to token address pairs
```

4. Start the provider server by running:
```bash
flask run --port=8030
```

5. Refer to the API.md file for endpoints and payloads.

That's it! You now have your own provider up and running.

Author: christian_casazza
Content: @OceanGPT Explain in detail the metadataCreated and metadataUpdated events

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
Sure, I can explain the metadataCreated and metadataUpdated events in detail.

The metadataCreated event is triggered when metadata for an asset is first published on-chain. The metadata is first compressed (using lzma) and encrypted, and then published on-chain. The metadata on-chain is not kept in storage, but rather is captured in an event log named MetadataCreated. This event contains information such as the address of the publisher, the metadata hash, and the block number.

The metadataUpdated event, on the other hand, is triggered when metadata for an asset is updated. This event contains information such as the address of the entity that updated the metadata, the state of the asset, the decryptor URL, the flags, the data, the metadata hash, the timestamp, and the block number.

Both events are important for tracking changes to the metadata of an asset on the Ocean Protocol network.

Author: christian_casazza
Content: @OceanGPT How does the provider check whether a wallet has the permissions to view the metadata information of an asset

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: The provider checks whether a wallet has the permissions to view the metadata information of an asset by checking the access control list (ACL) stored on the blockchain. The ACL specifies which Ethereum addresses have permission to access the metadata. When a user requests access to the metadata, the provider checks the user's Ethereum address against the ACL to determine whether the user has permission to access the metadata. If the user has permission, the provider decrypts and decompresses the metadata and returns it to the user. If the user does not have permission, the provider denies the request and does not provide access to the metadata.

Author: christian_casazza
Content: @OceanGPT Is there a difference between a wallet having permission to view metadata information of an asset and having permission to access the data asset itself?

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: Yes, there is a difference. Having permission to view metadata information of an asset means that the wallet can see the information about the asset, such as its name, description, and creator, but cannot access the actual data asset itself. On the other hand, having permission to access the data asset means that the wallet can retrieve and use the actual data asset. The provider can check whether a wallet has the permissions to view the metadata information of an asset by checking the access control list (ACL) associated with the asset's DID. The ACL specifies which Ethereum addresses have permission to view the metadata information and/or access the data asset.

Author: christian_casazza
Content: @OceanGPT How can a publisher implement fine-grained access controls to determine who can view the metadata information

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: One way a publisher can implement fine-grained access controls to determine who can view the metadata information is by restricting metadata caching to publishers in a specific list of publisher addresses. This list, called ALLOWED_PUBLISHERS, would contain the addresses of publishers who are authorized to view the metadata information. The metadata itself is first compressed and encrypted before being published on-chain, and is captured in an event log named MetadataCreated. The Aquarius service defers to the Provider for encryption and decryption, and supports utf-8 encoded strings. The Provider can check whether a wallet has the permissions to view the metadata information of an asset by checking if the wallet's address is included in the ALLOWED_PUBLISHERS list. There is a difference between a wallet having permission to view metadata information of an asset and having permission to access the data asset itself. Access to the data asset itself would require additional permissions and authentication.

Author: christian_casazza
Content: @OceanGPT is the metadata information that is kept inside of Aquarius a copy of the metadata information encrypted and stored on-chain?

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: No, the metadata information kept inside of Aquarius is not a copy of the metadata information encrypted and stored on-chain. Instead, Aquarius caches the metadata information that is published on-chain and stores it in an Elasticsearch database. The metadata is first compressed and encrypted before being published on-chain, and Aquarius defers to the Provider for encryption and decryption.

Author: christian_casazza
Content: @OceanGPT What is the difference between caching the metadata information and copying the metadata information?

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: Caching the metadata information involves storing a copy of the metadata on a separate system, such as Elasticsearch, for faster search and retrieval. Copying the metadata information refers to publishing the metadata on-chain, which is the initial step in the process of creating a new asset. So, caching is a performance optimization technique, while copying is a necessary step in the asset creation process.

Content: @OceanGPT As far as I know there can be multiple datatokens created for the same DataNFT using the existing Ocean Protocol JavaScript libraries. Could you show me some code how to add a new datatoken to my DataNFT with JavaScript?

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
Sure, here's some sample code to add a new datatoken to an existing DataNFT using Ocean Protocol JavaScript libraries:

```
const ocean = await Ocean.getInstance({
  web3Provider: web3,
  nodeUri: 'https://your.node.uri',
  aquariusUri: 'https://your.aquarius.uri',
  brizoUri: 'https://your.brizo.uri',
  verbose: true
})

const dataToken = await ocean.datatokens.create('MyNewDataToken', 'MNDT', 'My new datatoken description')
const dataNFT = await ocean.assets.create('MyDataNFT', 'MDN', 'My data NFT description', 'https://mydataurl.com')

await ocean.assets.addDataToken(dataNFT.id, dataToken.address)
```

This code creates a new datatoken called "MyNewDataToken" with the symbol "MNDT" and a description, and then creates a new DataNFT called "MyDataNFT" with a description and a URL. Finally, it adds the new datatoken to the DataNFT using the `addDataToken` method.

You can repeat the `ocean.datatokens.create` and `ocean.assets.addDataToken` steps to add multiple datatokens to the same DataNFT.

### IPFS

[IPFS](https://ipfs.io/) is a peer-to-peer protocol for sharing and storing hypermedia in a distributed file system. IPFS allows you to store and share files in a decentralized way, without relying on a central server.

**Step 1 - Install IPFS**

Install IPFS on your local machine by following the instructions on the [official IPFS website](https://docs.ipfs.io/install/).

**Step 2 - Add file to IPFS**

Add the file you wish to host to IPFS by running the following command in your terminal:

```
ipfs add <file>
```

This will return a CID (Content Identifier) for the file.

**Step 3 - Copy the CID**

Copy the CID from the output of the previous command.

![IPFS add file output](../.gitbook/assets/ipfs-1.png)

This CID will be used as the `CID` field when publishing the asset on Ocean Marketplace.

## Centralized hosting

### Amazon S3

[Amazon S3](https://aws.amazon.com/s3/) is a highly scalable, secure, and durable object storage service. It is designed to store and retrieve any amount of data from anywhere on the web.

**Step 1 - Create an S3 bucket**

Create a new S3 bucket in your AWS account by following the instructions in the [official AWS documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/gsg/CreatingABucket.html).

**Step 2 - Upload file to S3**

Upload the file you wish to host to the S3 bucket by following the instructions in the [official AWS documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/upload-objects.html).

**Step 3 - Get the S3 URL**

Get the URL of the uploaded file by following the instructions in the [official AWS documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/ShareObjectPreSignedURL.html).

### Google Cloud Storage

[Google Cloud Storage](https://cloud.google.com/storage) is a highly scalable and durable object storage service. It is designed to store and retrieve any amount of data from anywhere on the web.

**Step 1 - Create a Cloud Storage bucket**

Create a new Cloud Storage bucket in your Google Cloud account by following the instructions in the [official Google Cloud documentation](https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/creating-buckets).

**Step 2 - Upload file to Cloud Storage**

Upload the file you wish to host to the Cloud Storage bucket by following the instructions in the [official Google Cloud documentation](https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/uploading-objects).

**Step 3 - Get the Cloud Storage URL**

Get the URL of the uploaded file by following the instructions in the [official Google Cloud documentation](https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/access-public-data#gsutil).

This URL will be used as the `link` field when publishing the asset on Ocean Marketplace.

Author: lukas85#6738
Content: @OceanGPT explain a motion to demurrer

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: A motion to demurrer is a legal motion made by a defendant in response to a complaint filed by a plaintiff. The motion argues that even if all the allegations in the complaint are true, they do not constitute a legal claim or cause of action. In other words, the defendant is saying that the plaintiff has failed to state a claim upon which relief can be granted. The purpose of a demurrer is to challenge the legal sufficiency of the complaint and to ask the court to dismiss the case. If the court grants the demurrer, the plaintiff may be given an opportunity to amend the complaint to address the deficiencies identified by the defendant.

It argues that even if all the allegations in the complaint are true, they do not state a valid legal claim. The motion asks the court to dismiss the complaint without allowing the plaintiff to amend it.

an you explain the ocean objective function?

The Ocean objective function is a mathematical formula used to optimize the allocation of data assets in the Ocean network. It takes into account various factors such as the quality of the data, the price, and the demand for the data to determine the most efficient way to allocate the data assets. The objective function is designed to ensure that data providers are incentivized to provide high-quality data, while data consumers are able to access the data they need at a fair price.

What can you do with Ocean?

With Ocean, you can create and participate in a decentralized data marketplace where you can buy and sell data assets securely and transparently. You can also use Ocean to publish your own data assets and earn revenue from their use. Additionally, Ocean provides tools and infrastructure for building data-driven applications and services.

You can find Ocean documentation and code examples on the official Ocean Protocol website and GitHub repository. The documentation includes detailed guides on how to use Ocean, while the code examples provide sample code for common use cases and scenarios. Author: pikachudot
Content: @OceanGPT how can i setup a dispenser without barge

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: Generating something hopefully smart, give me a moment...

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
In Minecraft, setting up a dispenser without a barge is quite simple. Here's a step-by-step guide:

1. **Collect the necessary materials**: You will need 7 cobblestones, 1 bow, and 1 redstone dust to craft a dispenser. You can find cobblestones commonly by mining stone blocks, craft a bow using 3 sticks and 3 strings, and obtain redstone dust by mining redstone ore.

2. **Craft the dispenser**: Open your crafting table and place the 7 cobblestones in a U shape, the bow in the middle slot, and the redstone dust in the bottom middle slot. This will create a dispenser.

3. **Choose a location**: Decide where you want to place your dispenser. It can be on the ground, on a wall, or even facing downwards or upwards.

4. **Place the dispenser**: Select the dispenser in your hotbar and right-click on the surface where you want to place it. The dispenser's direction will be facing you when you place it.

5. **Load the dispenser**: Right-click on the dispenser to open its interface. You can place up to 9 different items in it, which it will dispense one at a time when activated.

6. **Activate the dispenser**: You can activate the dispenser by using redstone power. This can be a redstone torch, a block of redstone, a lever, a button, or any other redstone activation device. When the dispenser is powered, it will dispense one of the items inside.

Remember, the dispenser will shoot out most items as entities, but it will use certain items as if they were being used by a player (like arrows, eggs, or potions).

[Saturday, October 28, 2023 at 10:49:30 PM UTC] OceanGPT: To create a DataToken using ocean.js, you need to follow these steps:

1. First, you need to import the Ocean and DataTokens classes from ocean.js:

```javascript
import { Ocean, DataTokens } from '@oceanprotocol/lib'
```

2. Initialize the Ocean instance:

```javascript
const ocean = await Ocean.getInstance(config)
```

3. Create a new DataToken:

```javascript
const datatoken = new DataTokens(
  '0x123', // This is the address of the DataToken contract
  ocean.web3
)
```

Please replace '0x123' with the address of your DataToken contract. The second argument is the web3 instance from the Ocean object.

Remember to have your environment properly set up with the necessary dependencies and configurations.

Author: pikachudot
Content: how can i create a dispenser from a datatoken in ocean.js @OceanGPT

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: Generating something hopefully smart, give me a moment...

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
To create a dispenser from a datatoken using ocean.js, you need to follow these steps:

1. First, you need to initialize Ocean and get the account. Here is an example:

```javascript
import { Ocean, ConfigHelper } from '@oceanprotocol/lib'

const config = new ConfigHelper().getConfig('rinkeby')
const ocean = await Ocean.getInstance(config)

// Accounts
const account = (await ocean.accounts.list())[0]
```

2. Then, you need to create a new datatoken:

```javascript
const datatoken = await ocean.datatokens.create('https://example.com', account)
```

3. After that, you can create a dispenser:

```javascript
const dispenserAddress = await ocean.dispenser.createDispenser(datatoken, account)
```

4. Finally, you can approve and request datatokens:

```javascript
await ocean.dispenser.approve(datatoken, 100, account)
await ocean.dispenser.requestTokens(datatoken, 100, account)
```

Please note that you need to replace `'https://example.com'` with your own URL, and `100` with the amount of datatokens you want to approve and request. Also, make sure that the account you are using has enough balance to create and request datatokens.

Content: @OceanGPT how can i create a fre token with a dispenser

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: Generating something hopefully smart, give me a moment...

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
Creating a Fre token with a dispenser involves a few steps. Here's a simplified guide:

1. **Create a Wallet**: You need a wallet that supports NEAR Protocol. You can create one on the official NEAR Wallet website.

2. **Buy NEAR Tokens**: You need NEAR tokens to pay for transaction fees. You can buy NEAR tokens on exchanges like Binance, Huobi, etc.

3. **Create a Fre Token**: Visit the Mintbase website and connect your NEAR wallet. Click on "Mint a Thing" and follow the instructions to create your Fre token.

4. **Create a Dispenser**: After creating your Fre token, go to the "My Market" section and click on "Create Dispenser". Set the price and amount of Fre tokens you want to dispense.

5. **Fund the Dispenser**: Click on "Fund Dispenser" and confirm the transaction in your NEAR wallet. The dispenser will now automatically sell your Fre tokens to anyone who sends the correct amount of NEAR tokens to it.

Remember, this is a simplified guide. The actual process may involve more steps and require a deeper understanding of blockchain technology and the NEAR Protocol. Always do your own research and consider seeking advice from professionals or experienced users.

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content: Generating something hopefully smart, give me a moment...

Author: OceanGPT#0740
Content:
Unstaking Ocean tokens can be done through the Ocean Protocol's official website or through the platform where you staked your tokens. Here's a general guide on how to do it:

1. Visit the Ocean Protocol's official website or the platform where you staked your Ocean tokens.

2. Navigate to the staking section. This could be under "Your Stakes", "Your Investments", or a similar section.

3. Find the Ocean tokens that you have staked. There should be an option to manage or view your stakes.

4. Click on the "Unstake" or "Withdraw" button. This will initiate the unstaking process.

5. Confirm the transaction. You may need to pay a small gas fee for the transaction to be processed.

6. Wait for the transaction to be confirmed. Once it's confirmed, your Ocean tokens will be unstaked and returned to your wallet.

Remember, the exact process may vary depending on the platform you're using. Always make sure to double-check the transaction details before confirming to avoid any mistakes.
